So if they're giving
you a loan, they

00:11:41.990 --> 00:11:45.230
want to make sure that you can
cover the loan and the mortgage

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:48.150
payment at the same time.

00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:49.380
OK?

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:50.290
Credit cards.

00:11:50.290 --> 00:11:52.140
Do you have any credit cards?

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:55.220
Nobody says you have to pay
off all your credit cards,

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:57.730
but you want to make sure
that they're on time,

00:11:57.730 --> 00:12:01.720
and you want to make sure that
the balance is not as high.

00:12:01.720 --> 00:12:04.540
So if your credit card
is a $5,000 credit card,

00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:06.710
you don't want to be at $4,000.

00:12:06.710 --> 00:12:11.960
You want to be below, below
half, and also on time.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:13.710
Negative history.

00:12:13.710 --> 00:12:17.110
Use this form to write
down any negative history

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:19.250
you may have on your credit.

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:21.500
Because that is something
that's not going to go away.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:23.590
When you try to go to
a bank and get a loan,

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:25.173
they're going to
look at these things,

00:12:25.173 --> 00:12:27.610
and they're going to ask
you, what's up with this?

00:12:27.610 --> 00:12:28.900
What's up with that?

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:30.960
Make sure it's not in judgment.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:32.160
Call up those companies.

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:35.920
A lot of people go to these
credit repair companies.

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:38.000
I don't advise it.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.450
A lot of these credit repair
companies, they're scams.

00:12:41.450 --> 00:12:45.095
Unless you go to a nonprofit
agency, don't do it.

00:12:45.095 --> 00:12:46.470
They're doing--
they're not doing

00:12:46.470 --> 00:12:48.670
nothing you can't do yourself.

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:51.440
Basically, when you go
to the credit report,

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:54.960
you can go and dispute
these credit ratings.

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:55.870
OK?

00:12:55.870 --> 00:12:57.930
Sometimes you just
have to pay it off.

00:12:57.930 --> 00:13:00.300
Sometimes, if you
can't pay it off fully,

00:13:00.300 --> 00:13:02.250
you could do a settlement.

00:13:02.250 --> 00:13:04.670
But a settlement
will show, you know,

00:13:04.670 --> 00:13:06.270
it won't be as great
as paying it off

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:08.120
because it shows
that you settled,

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:10.980
but at least it's off
your credit as well.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:14.230
All I'm saying to you is, you
have to look at these things

00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:17.310
before you start to go buy
a house because the loan

00:13:17.310 --> 00:13:19.590
officer will look at them.

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:22.350
You also may not know that maybe
somebody is using your credit

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:23.840
that you didn't know.

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:26.920
I spoke to this
gentleman, and his father,

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:30.780
who has the same name as
him, was using his credit.

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:32.000
Yeah.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.230
So he had no idea,
because he had not

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:35.780
checked his credit report.

00:13:35.780 --> 00:13:37.820
So now he's coming
to go buy a house,

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:40.010
and he's seeing this credit.

00:13:40.010 --> 00:13:43.060
I know another guy had
not used his credit,

00:13:43.060 --> 00:13:48.140
had not checked this credit, saw
a student loan on his credit.

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:49.220
I couldn't believe it.

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:51.830
I could not believe he had a
student loan on his credit.

00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:52.996
And he didn't go to college.

00:13:56.320 --> 00:13:59.665
So you need to check and make
sure that those things that are

00:13:59.665 --> 00:14:00.290
on your credit.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:02.300
Also, things on
your credit can not

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:05.590
be there for longer than seven
years once they're finished.

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:08.140
So if somebody is keeping
something on your credit,

00:14:08.140 --> 00:14:09.350
you need to dispute it.

00:14:09.350 --> 00:14:10.870
Disputing it is free.

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:13.010
It takes the--
just take the time.

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:15.140
The websites are
so much easier now.

00:14:15.140 --> 00:14:16.930
You can just put in
what the issue is.

00:14:16.930 --> 00:14:19.550
And by law-- I'm not a
lawyer-- but by law, they

00:14:19.550 --> 00:14:22.870
have to remove it off your
credit for a certain amount

00:14:22.870 --> 00:14:26.900
of days while they
contact the company

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:31.220
and find out if
it's valid or not.

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:34.520
After you write down what
you think your credit is,

00:14:34.520 --> 00:14:36.810
find out what your
credit really is now.

00:14:36.810 --> 00:14:37.540
Right?

00:14:37.540 --> 00:14:40.850
Credit scores go
between 500 and 800.

00:14:40.850 --> 00:14:43.510
Obviously 500 is
really, really bad.

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:45.510
800 is really, really good.

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:47.930
You have 800, you can
walk into any bank

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:50.160
and say, give me what I want.

00:14:50.160 --> 00:14:50.900
OK?

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:54.610
The three major credit companies
are Transunion, Equifax,

00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:58.670
and Experian, and if you go
to annualcreditreport.com,

00:14:58.670 --> 00:15:03.380
you can get a free credit
report every single year.

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:10.390
What I personally do is I
subscribe to one of these,

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:13.940
and it gives me an alert
every time my credit goes up,

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:18.930
every time my credit goes down,
anytime someone runs my credit.

00:15:18.930 --> 00:15:21.920
Anything that happens to
my credit, I get a notice.

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:24.950
And I can get my credit
report any time I want.

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:29.329
So for a couple bucks a month
you can get one of those.

00:15:29.329 --> 00:15:30.620
AUDIENCE: Can we ask questions?

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:31.703
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Yes.

00:15:31.703 --> 00:15:32.240
Absolutely.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:33.906
AUDIENCE: I have a
couple of credit cards

00:15:33.906 --> 00:15:34.740
I don't really use.

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:38.172
I use them once every few months
just so that they stay active.

00:15:38.172 --> 00:15:39.589
They don't go dormant.

00:15:39.589 --> 00:15:41.714
But if, given that that I
have a lot of credit that

00:15:41.714 --> 00:15:43.485
is available to me
that I'm not using,

00:15:43.485 --> 00:15:45.410
is that actually
hurting my credit score,

00:15:45.410 --> 00:15:46.692
or is that helping?

00:15:46.692 --> 00:15:47.900
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: It can.

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:50.530
A loan officer will look
at that, and it can hurt.

00:15:50.530 --> 00:15:53.870
Because they can give you a
loan today for a house for like,

00:15:53.870 --> 00:15:56.250
let's say, $800,000.

00:15:56.250 --> 00:15:58.900
And their fear is that the
next day you max it out

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:00.030
with furniture or whatever.

00:16:00.030 --> 00:16:02.110
And now you've put
yourself in debt

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:04.240
that's going to hurt you
from paying your loan.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:07.060
So yes, it can
hurt a little bit.

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:10.432
But until you are really ready,
you don't have to close it.

00:16:10.432 --> 00:16:12.140
Because when you speak
to a loan officer,

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:13.700
as long as they're
paid and everything,

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:15.920
loan officer will probably
just say, hey close, this one.

00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:16.550
Close that one.

00:16:16.550 --> 00:16:19.042
Close that one, And
that's not a big deal.

00:16:19.042 --> 00:16:19.750
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:21.750
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS:
You're welcome.

00:16:21.750 --> 00:16:24.082
OK.

00:16:24.082 --> 00:16:24.582
Oh.

00:16:34.050 --> 00:16:35.670
Your money.

00:16:35.670 --> 00:16:38.640
You will need money
to buy a house, right?

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:41.810
I know sometimes you can go
to a car, a car dealership,

00:16:41.810 --> 00:16:45.310
and they say, you know,
0% down, 0% financing.

00:16:45.310 --> 00:16:45.810
No.

00:16:45.810 --> 00:16:48.310
When you buy a house,
you will need money.

00:16:48.310 --> 00:16:50.270
So this is something on
the worksheet for you

00:16:50.270 --> 00:16:54.170
to look at yourself and say, how
much money do I have saved up?

00:16:54.170 --> 00:16:56.660
How much money can I
put towards my house?

00:16:56.660 --> 00:16:59.750
You may have a 401(k)
plan, a retirement plan.

00:16:59.750 --> 00:17:02.540
Well, many people don't
know, with your 401(k) plan,

00:17:02.540 --> 00:17:07.099
you're allowed to take $10,000
out your retirement money

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:11.529
without penalty for the
purchase of a house.

00:17:11.529 --> 00:17:12.028
Yes?

00:17:12.028 --> 00:17:13.694
AUDIENCE: Is it
possible to borrow money

00:17:13.694 --> 00:17:15.310
from your own 401(k)?

00:17:15.310 --> 00:17:16.839
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: You can.

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:17.790
Everyone is different.

00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:20.119
So you have to check
with your particular one,

00:17:20.119 --> 00:17:23.319
but I do know you can take
$10,000 without penalty,

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:26.510
but it has to be for
the purchase of a home.

00:17:26.510 --> 00:17:27.010
OK?

00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:28.310
AUDIENCE: It has to be for the--

00:17:28.310 --> 00:17:29.726
TRISHA OCONA
FRANCIS: The $10,000?

00:17:29.726 --> 00:17:32.340
The $10,000 has to be for
the purchase of a home.

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:33.360
Gifts.

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:35.370
Yes, sorry.

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:36.072
Go a--

00:17:36.072 --> 00:17:38.532
AUDIENCE: Is the $10,000, is
that per-- so a couple buying

00:17:38.532 --> 00:17:40.500
together, is that per person?

00:17:40.500 --> 00:17:41.490
Or is--

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:43.823
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: I've
seen people do it separately.

00:17:43.823 --> 00:17:48.085
I think it's per
person's 401(k).

00:17:48.085 --> 00:17:48.585
Yes?

00:17:48.585 --> 00:17:51.060
AUDIENCE: That $10k, is that
for your primary residency?

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:53.350
Can you use it for like
an investment property?

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:54.600
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Primary.

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:58.140
But like I said, check with
your-- because everyone,

00:17:58.140 --> 00:18:00.820
I've seen so many different
401(k)s, and you know,

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:02.410
they call it the
401(3) sometimes,

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:06.470
have different provisions,
so check with that one.

00:18:06.470 --> 00:18:08.272
Gifts.

00:18:08.272 --> 00:18:10.730
Maybe you just got married,
and your parents are giving you

00:18:10.730 --> 00:18:12.330
money to buy a house.

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:18.040
I know a couple, and
the husband's father

00:18:18.040 --> 00:18:20.700
had silver coins.

00:18:20.700 --> 00:18:23.240
And he traded them in,
and he took the money,

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:25.090
and he split it
between his two sons,

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:27.010
and that's what they
used to buy the house.

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:29.840
Here's the thing with gifts.

00:18:29.840 --> 00:18:33.940
They're going to trace where
that person got the money from.

00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:34.510
OK?

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:37.970
Because they want to avoid
any money laundering.

00:18:37.970 --> 00:18:40.275
So if someone is giving
you a gift, a lot of times

00:18:40.275 --> 00:18:42.900
they're going to have to sign an
affidavit that this was a gift

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:45.056
also, that it was not a loan.

00:18:45.056 --> 00:18:46.680
The bank wants to
make sure that you're

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:49.190
not-- they're not
giving you this money

00:18:49.190 --> 00:18:52.145
and then you have to pay it
back on top of that loan.

00:18:52.145 --> 00:18:53.520
So if it is a
gift, they're going

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.160
to have to say it's a gift.

00:18:55.160 --> 00:18:58.170
And if there's a gift, it's
going to go into your account,

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:00.660
and they're going to have to
trace where that person got it

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:01.250
from.

00:19:01.250 --> 00:19:04.022
Because the IRS wants
all that reported.

00:19:04.022 --> 00:19:06.480
And if you have any other money,
if you have anything else.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:06.980
Yes?

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:09.830
AUDIENCE: So if it's a gift, do
you have to pay different tax?

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:12.330
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: It depends
on, I mean, you're allowed,

00:19:12.330 --> 00:19:13.500
depending on who
you're getting it

00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:15.060
from-- I'm not an
accountant-- but it

00:19:15.060 --> 00:19:18.830
depends on who you're getting
it from, and how much it is.

00:19:18.830 --> 00:19:19.350
Right?

00:19:19.350 --> 00:19:22.100
But if they do give you,
you have-- they're basically

00:19:22.100 --> 00:19:24.660
just checking to make
sure that this wasn't

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:26.820
drug money under the mattress.

00:19:26.820 --> 00:19:31.480
So but other than that, you
know, if it's like $10,000,

00:19:31.480 --> 00:19:33.360
you know, it could be
from a parent, right?

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:35.901
So a parent is allowed to give
you a certain amount of gifts.

00:19:35.901 --> 00:19:40.100
But also, my disclaimer is
check with your accountant.

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:41.720
Any other money?

00:19:41.720 --> 00:19:44.160
I know a new couple
who was getting ready,

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:47.180
they were selling their car
so they could have more money

00:19:47.180 --> 00:19:48.550
to buy their house.

00:19:48.550 --> 00:19:49.370
OK?

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:52.230
How much money will
you really need?

00:19:52.230 --> 00:19:53.950
Well, it depends.

00:19:53.950 --> 00:19:56.560
If you're going an FHA
first time homebuyer

00:19:56.560 --> 00:19:59.750
loan-- your first
time buying a home,

00:19:59.750 --> 00:20:03.140
you're getting an FHA
loan-- you need 3 and 1/2%.

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:05.680
3 and 1/2% of whatever
the loan is, that's

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:07.940
what you're going to
need for the house.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:08.730
OK?

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:13.330
Conventional or, if you're a
vet, you can get a VA loan.

00:20:13.330 --> 00:20:15.570
These are the type of
loans you should explore

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:17.230
with the mortgage
person that you're

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:19.740
dealing with to see
what rates they have,

00:20:19.740 --> 00:20:21.550
what programs they have.

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:23.860
There are many different
types of loans.

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:27.650
But FHA, just to note, is a
first time homebuyer loan-- 3

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:29.060
and 1/2%.

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:30.760
You also need closing costs.

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:33.300
Closing costs is going to
pay for the filing fees.

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:35.070
It's going to pay
for your attorney.

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:41.910
Closing cost is anywhere
between 4% to 6% of the loan.

00:20:41.910 --> 00:20:44.120
That, give or take, if
you want to calculate

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:45.920
how much money you will need.

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:49.100
So whatever the purchase
price of your home, 3 and 1/2%

00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:52.340
of that will be your down
payment, about 4% to 6% of that

00:20:52.340 --> 00:20:54.480
will be for your closing costs.

00:20:54.480 --> 00:20:57.310
How much is the value of
your home is going to be?

00:20:57.310 --> 00:20:59.450
That depends on what
the bank qualifies you

00:20:59.450 --> 00:21:04.130
for based on your income,
based on your debt.

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:04.860
OK?

00:21:04.860 --> 00:21:07.430
You also have
something called PMI.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:11.640
PMI is, if you purchase a
home, and you put down--

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:14.930
now the average for
FHA is 3 and 1/2%--

00:21:14.930 --> 00:21:18.920
but if you put down less than
20%, which 3 and 1/2% is,

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:23.400
you are considered a risk to
the bank, which means that,

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:25.470
God forbid you
were to foreclose,

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:30.110
there's a short margin
to sell the home back.

00:21:30.110 --> 00:21:33.510
If you put down less
than 20% of the loan,

00:21:33.510 --> 00:21:37.410
the bank will charge you PMI.

00:21:37.410 --> 00:21:40.830
That is an insurance to
protect them in case you

00:21:40.830 --> 00:21:42.430
default on your loan.

00:21:42.430 --> 00:21:45.830
But, with all this
training, you won't do that.

00:21:45.830 --> 00:21:46.700
OK?

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:49.130
Owner occupant
versus investment,

00:21:49.130 --> 00:21:50.350
that's something else.

00:21:50.350 --> 00:21:53.000
If you get a first
time homebuyer loan,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.760
you have to live there.

00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:57.720
It's to help people
become homeowners,

00:21:57.720 --> 00:21:59.860
so you have to live there.

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:02.190
There's also loans
for investors.

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:04.801
So if you have a home already,
you don't plan to live there,

00:22:04.801 --> 00:22:06.800
and this is just going
to be an investment home,

00:22:06.800 --> 00:22:08.050
you can do that.

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:09.980
I also want to take
a second to let

00:22:09.980 --> 00:22:11.480
you understand
what's the difference

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:13.330
between a banker and a broker.

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:15.870
I learned this the hard way.

00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:19.040
When you go for a loan,
find out from the person,

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:20.280
are you a banker?

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:22.020
Or are you a broker?

00:22:22.020 --> 00:22:24.990
A banker is the
person with the money.

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:29.380
They're the one
lending you directly.

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:32.470
A broker is the one
shopping the loan for you.

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:34.980
So what does that mean?

00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:38.080
They come with a cost.

00:22:38.080 --> 00:22:41.550
Why would someone go to
a broker versus a banker?

00:22:41.550 --> 00:22:44.150
Maybe your income
is not that high.

00:22:44.150 --> 00:22:47.630
Maybe your credit
is not that great.

00:22:47.630 --> 00:22:50.780
So the broker gathers
all your information

00:22:50.780 --> 00:22:54.200
and shops it out
to different banks.

00:22:54.200 --> 00:22:56.710
Believe it or not,
you are paying

00:22:56.710 --> 00:22:59.540
that broker for that service.

00:22:59.540 --> 00:23:02.750
So your closing cost
is going to be high.

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:05.480
I've seen people pay up
to $20,000 for that broker

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:07.685
in their closing
costs and not realize

00:23:07.685 --> 00:23:10.060
they were paying that broker
why their closing costs were

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:11.790
so high.

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:16.820
A banker would be going up to
Chase, Bank of America, Wells

00:23:16.820 --> 00:23:19.140
Fargo, one of these banks.

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:20.940
That would be a banker.

00:23:20.940 --> 00:23:21.700
OK?

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:25.190
A broker would be
another company

00:23:25.190 --> 00:23:27.820
who's shopping it for you.

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:28.798
Yes?

00:23:28.798 --> 00:23:30.710
AUDIENCE: 3 and 1/2% and 20%.

00:23:30.710 --> 00:23:31.670
I don't understand.

00:23:31.670 --> 00:23:32.711
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: OK.

00:23:32.711 --> 00:23:35.570
So an FHA loan is a first
time homebuyer loan.

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:38.830
And in order as an incentive to
become a first time homebuyer,

00:23:38.830 --> 00:23:42.100
you only have to put down
3 and 1/2% of the loan

00:23:42.100 --> 00:23:44.594
as your down payment, as
your part of the investment.

00:23:44.594 --> 00:23:46.260
Why the bank makes
you do an investment?

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:48.420
Because, you know,
if someone is asking

00:23:48.420 --> 00:23:51.910
you to go into business with
them, and they're saying, hey,

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:54.149
I can I borrow $90 grand?

00:23:54.149 --> 00:23:56.690
You're going to say, well, how
much money are you putting up?

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:59.230
So that's why the bank wants
you to put up something.

00:23:59.230 --> 00:24:01.840
So you're putting up 3 and 1/2%.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:06.190
Now, you're still considered
a risk because you only put up

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:08.120
3 and 1/2%.

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:11.890
If you put up 20%,
you're no longer a risk.

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:13.940
Because if you
default on the loan,

00:24:13.940 --> 00:24:16.930
and the bank has to sell it
at auction in a foreclosure,

00:24:16.930 --> 00:24:20.960
they still have this 20% cushion
that they can make it back

00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:21.710
with.

00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:23.770
3 and 1/2%, anything
could happen.

00:24:23.770 --> 00:24:27.630
The market could drop, the
property could need repairs,

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:30.010
and they may go underwater.

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:33.200
So that's why, if you
put down less than 20%,

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:36.500
they make you pay
PMI-- Premium Mortgage

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.130
Insurance-- to cover
them, and protect them,

00:24:39.130 --> 00:24:40.670
in case you default. Yes?

00:24:40.670 --> 00:24:44.149
AUDIENCE: So then in the case
you're a first housebuyer,

00:24:44.149 --> 00:24:47.090
and you put 20%, then you don't
need to pay the PMI anymore?

00:24:47.090 --> 00:24:48.340
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Correct.

00:24:48.340 --> 00:24:49.210
Now it depends.

00:24:49.210 --> 00:24:50.180
They changed the law.

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:55.140
So now, on an FHA loan, the PMI
is for the life of the loan.

00:24:55.140 --> 00:24:56.840
It never was like that.

00:24:56.840 --> 00:24:59.650
On a conventional
loan, so in order--

00:24:59.650 --> 00:25:02.610
if you get an FHA loan, if you
want to get out of the PMI--

00:25:02.610 --> 00:25:07.520
because PMI could be like $450
a month added to your loan--

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:09.930
if you want to get
out of the PMI,

00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:12.070
you would have to
refinance out the loan.

00:25:12.070 --> 00:25:16.210
On conventional,
once you get 20%

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:19.840
in equity, which means either
you've paid down your mortgage,

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:24.510
or the value of your house has
gone up, you can call them up

00:25:24.510 --> 00:25:27.875
and say, I'm by it, I'm
20%, take off my PMI.

00:25:27.875 --> 00:25:30.250
But you have to call them,
because they won't take it off

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:31.560
on theirself.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:33.101
OK?

00:25:33.101 --> 00:25:33.600
Yes.

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:34.074
AUDIENCE: Is there
any way for a tenant

00:25:34.074 --> 00:25:36.602
to go to bank for a
mortgage, than to go

00:25:36.602 --> 00:25:38.296
to broker for mortgage?

00:25:38.296 --> 00:25:39.670
TRISHA OCONA
FRANCIS: Absolutely.

00:25:39.670 --> 00:25:41.128
Like I said, the
only reason people

00:25:41.128 --> 00:25:44.404
go to a broker is because they
don't have that much income,

00:25:44.404 --> 00:25:45.820
or their credit
is not that great.

00:25:45.820 --> 00:25:48.130
But you have to pay
them for their service.

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:51.210
Whereas a banker, you're going
directly to the person who has,

00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:53.020
the entity that has the money.

00:25:53.020 --> 00:25:55.392
So what's a good way to
do it is, a lot of times,

00:25:55.392 --> 00:25:57.600
you know, you're shopping
and people run your credit.

00:25:57.600 --> 00:25:59.220
Every time you run your
credit, your credit rating

00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:00.490
goes a little bit down.

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:02.390
They do understand
that you're shopping,

00:26:02.390 --> 00:26:04.010
so they give you a little way.

00:26:04.010 --> 00:26:06.630
But you want to make sure
that that one or two points

00:26:06.630 --> 00:26:08.090
don't really hurt you.

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:11.360
Go to annualcreditreport.com,
get a copy of your credit

00:26:11.360 --> 00:26:15.330
report, do the tasks that
I gave you, and go to them

00:26:15.330 --> 00:26:18.410
and say, listen, this is my
credit, this is my score,

00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:20.320
what can you do for me?

00:26:20.320 --> 00:26:22.180
Do not pull my credit.

00:26:22.180 --> 00:26:25.140
Because they pull your credit,
it would be a hard pull,

00:26:25.140 --> 00:26:27.690
and you can lose a point or
two every time somebody pulls

00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:28.220
your credit.

00:26:28.220 --> 00:26:30.594
Because what it looks like is
you're just shopping around

00:26:30.594 --> 00:26:32.010
for credit, credit, credit.

00:26:32.010 --> 00:26:32.765
Yes?

00:26:32.765 --> 00:26:34.348
AUDIENCE: Is there
any online resource

00:26:34.348 --> 00:26:36.681
where I can compare [? ten ?]
bank rates before actually

00:26:36.681 --> 00:26:38.840
going to go see them?

00:26:38.840 --> 00:26:40.710
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS:
What their rates are?

00:26:40.710 --> 00:26:41.210
Yeah.

00:26:41.210 --> 00:26:42.943
There's a, yeah,
there's a website like--

00:26:42.943 --> 00:26:43.984
ABBY ONTODD: Bizrate.com.

00:26:43.984 --> 00:26:46.234
AUDIENCE: And they don't
know my credit, I just check.

00:26:46.234 --> 00:26:48.924
ABBY ONTODD: No, it just
compares the rates of credit,

00:26:48.924 --> 00:26:53.380
you know, what they're
offering for mortgages.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:56.950
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: That's
Abby Ontodd, my assistant.

00:26:56.950 --> 00:26:57.450
OK.

00:26:57.450 --> 00:27:00.400
So here, yes?

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:02.687
AUDIENCE: What do you
think about LendingTree?

00:27:02.687 --> 00:27:04.645
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: I
don't really, you know,

00:27:04.645 --> 00:27:08.760
I don't endorse any
particular bank.

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:10.640
Right?

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:13.870
I don't-- I've seen some, you
know, do good, some do bad.

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:16.770
I think what you just need to do
is just, at the end of the day,

00:27:16.770 --> 00:27:20.580
make sure that they are
fulfilling what you need.

00:27:20.580 --> 00:27:21.350
Right?

00:27:21.350 --> 00:27:23.808
The interest rate, make sure
the interest rate is something

00:27:23.808 --> 00:27:24.840
you're comfortable with.

00:27:24.840 --> 00:27:28.442
Make sure the down payment, make
sure all those things stand.

00:27:28.442 --> 00:27:30.650
And then make sure you have
a really good real estate

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:33.090
agent and a real
estate attorney who

00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:36.330
is going to be with you
throughout the process

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:39.460
to make sure that
the i's are dotted,

00:27:39.460 --> 00:27:42.030
and the t's are crossed.

00:27:42.030 --> 00:27:42.720
OK.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:44.734
These are questions
to ask yourself also

00:27:44.734 --> 00:27:45.900
when you're starting to buy.

00:27:45.900 --> 00:27:48.066
A lot of people don't do
this until the last minute.

00:27:48.066 --> 00:27:49.660
Who do I want to buy with?

00:27:49.660 --> 00:27:52.320
You've got to be careful
who you want to buy with.

00:27:52.320 --> 00:27:54.890
Because, you know, buying with
someone is like a marriage.

00:27:54.890 --> 00:27:56.486
Once you're in, you're in.

00:27:56.486 --> 00:28:00.720
And in order to get out, either
through separation-- or even

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:03.950
death-- you have to figure
out, you have to plan ahead,

00:28:03.950 --> 00:28:06.690
is this somebody I
want to buy with?

00:28:06.690 --> 00:28:07.360
OK?

00:28:07.360 --> 00:28:09.504
How soon do I want to buy?

00:28:09.504 --> 00:28:11.170
I spoke to a lady the
other day, and she

00:28:11.170 --> 00:28:14.110
said she's been looking
for a house for a year.

00:28:14.110 --> 00:28:17.540
And she's not ready to buy then.

00:28:17.540 --> 00:28:19.550
Because the market is changing.

00:28:19.550 --> 00:28:22.180
The value of a home last year
is different from the value

00:28:22.180 --> 00:28:23.510
of a home this year.

00:28:23.510 --> 00:28:26.802
So if you do want to buy, you
need to look at when is it

00:28:26.802 --> 00:28:27.510
do I want to buy?

00:28:27.510 --> 00:28:29.560
You may not be ready
to buy now, but that's

00:28:29.560 --> 00:28:32.490
why this, this handout
is so important.

00:28:32.490 --> 00:28:34.991
Because it's preparing you
for when you do want to buy.

00:28:34.991 --> 00:28:36.740
You don't want to wake
up one day and say,

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:39.110
you know what, I'm
ready to buy, and then

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:41.940
you missed all these steps.

00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:45.490
So it's important to start with
these steps before you say,

00:28:45.490 --> 00:28:47.080
I'm going to buy.

00:28:47.080 --> 00:28:48.670
Right?

00:28:48.670 --> 00:28:52.830
You're going to need to take
some serious steps in order

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:54.940
to start purchasing your home.

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:58.600
If you don't have enough saved,
you're going to have to save.

00:28:58.600 --> 00:28:59.450
Right?

00:28:59.450 --> 00:29:03.005
You're going to
have to, you know,

00:29:03.005 --> 00:29:05.536
pull back on the
movies, or the clothes,

00:29:05.536 --> 00:29:06.660
or whatever you want to do.

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:09.090
You're going to have
to make commitments.

00:29:09.090 --> 00:29:10.580
And then, when you
purchase, you're

00:29:10.580 --> 00:29:11.900
going to have commitments.

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:14.520
Some people don't know that
when you purchase a home,

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:17.490
not only do you have the
home loan you've got to pay,

00:29:17.490 --> 00:29:18.780
you have interest on the loan.

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:23.140
It's called PITI--
Principal, Interest, Taxes,

00:29:23.140 --> 00:29:25.150
and Insurance-- you
have to pay on the home.

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:26.760
Plus you have utilities.

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:29.890
New York City, we
have water as well.

00:29:29.890 --> 00:29:31.596
You have property maintenance.

00:29:31.596 --> 00:29:32.970
These are all
things that are not

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:35.990
factored in when you're renting.

00:29:35.990 --> 00:29:40.400
So you have to make sure that
you're able to do those things.

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:45.230
Another thing that when you
get a loan what they look for,

00:29:45.230 --> 00:29:48.110
they look that you
have a steady income.

00:29:48.110 --> 00:29:49.607
You all have great jobs.

00:29:49.607 --> 00:29:50.940
That's what they're looking for.

00:29:50.940 --> 00:29:53.320
Because they want
to know that you

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:56.560
are going to be consistent
with paying this loan.

00:29:56.560 --> 00:29:58.480
If you have any
degrees, they want

00:29:58.480 --> 00:30:01.034
to look at that as well, right?

00:30:01.034 --> 00:30:02.450
God forbid you
lose your job, they

00:30:02.450 --> 00:30:03.830
know that you're employable.

00:30:03.830 --> 00:30:06.130
These are things that
they want to look at.

00:30:06.130 --> 00:30:08.970
They're going to want to
look at your tax returns,

00:30:08.970 --> 00:30:11.700
two to three years out.

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:12.480
Right?

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:15.322
Let's say you weren't here
before, you weren't here six

00:30:15.322 --> 00:30:17.280
months ago, but you were
working somewhere else

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:18.840
doing the same
thing that you do.

00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:19.539
That's OK.

00:30:19.539 --> 00:30:21.080
Because they want
to know that you're

00:30:21.080 --> 00:30:24.175
not jumping around from
industry to industry,

00:30:24.175 --> 00:30:25.550
that you're in
the same industry.

00:30:25.550 --> 00:30:27.870
Maybe you've changed
companies, but you're

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:30.615
in the same industry, which
means that you're consistent.

00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:37.690
Now, question.

00:30:37.690 --> 00:30:40.330
In a real estate transaction,
who does the real estate agent

00:30:40.330 --> 00:30:41.380
work for?

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:43.634
Does anyone know
the answer to this?

00:30:43.634 --> 00:30:44.134
Yes?

00:30:44.134 --> 00:30:45.009
AUDIENCE: It depends.

00:30:45.009 --> 00:30:48.490
If you're talking about the
buyer or seller's agent.

00:30:48.490 --> 00:30:50.140
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Right.

00:30:50.140 --> 00:30:51.030
Hear what he said?

00:30:51.030 --> 00:30:53.470
Depends on who
you're talking about.

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:55.730
Most people think
that the real estate

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:59.980
agent works for the seller.

00:30:59.980 --> 00:31:01.270
Wrong.

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:05.220
The real estate agent
works for whoever is hired.

00:31:05.220 --> 00:31:10.820
So someone can be a buyer,
and I can work for that buyer.

00:31:10.820 --> 00:31:13.560
And I'm working for that buyer,
trying to find that buyer

00:31:13.560 --> 00:31:17.050
the best house for
the cheapest price.

00:31:17.050 --> 00:31:21.180
Or I can work for the
seller, and at that point,

00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:26.210
I'm helping the seller sell
their home for the most money.

00:31:26.210 --> 00:31:29.559
Whoever you work for doesn't
determine who pays you.

00:31:29.559 --> 00:31:31.100
That's a little
secret that I'm going

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:32.550
to tell you that real estate
agents won't tell you.

00:31:32.550 --> 00:31:33.050
Yes?

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:35.550
AUDIENCE: My question
is on the seller.

00:31:35.550 --> 00:31:38.266
An agent gets paid like
a percentage of the deal.

00:31:38.266 --> 00:31:39.349
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Yes.

00:31:39.349 --> 00:31:42.283
AUDIENCE: So what's the
incentive for the buyer's agent

00:31:42.283 --> 00:31:45.502
to find the cheaper, the lower
price, because their percentage

00:31:45.502 --> 00:31:46.460
would be lower as well.

00:31:46.460 --> 00:31:48.600
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS:
Good question.

00:31:48.600 --> 00:31:50.761
They don't have an incentive.

00:31:50.761 --> 00:31:51.260
Right?

00:31:51.260 --> 00:31:53.340
His question is,
if a real estate

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:56.530
agent is paid by
commission, why would they

00:31:56.530 --> 00:32:00.410
help a buyer find
the cheapest house?

00:32:00.410 --> 00:32:02.510
Most of the time they won't.

00:32:02.510 --> 00:32:06.490
I would, because I do this
because I like doing this.

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:09.080
But my whole job is, like I
told you from the beginning,

00:32:09.080 --> 00:32:12.820
is to help people achieve
their real estate goals.

00:32:12.820 --> 00:32:13.630
Right?

00:32:13.630 --> 00:32:16.430
And if your real estate
goal is to get the best

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:19.176
house at the cheapest
price negotiated properly,

00:32:19.176 --> 00:32:20.550
then that's what
I'm going to do.

00:32:20.550 --> 00:32:22.140
But you're absolutely right.

00:32:22.140 --> 00:32:25.250
Most real estate agents will not
try to find the cheapest house,

00:32:25.250 --> 00:32:28.010
because they know that
the more expensive

00:32:28.010 --> 00:32:30.100
they help you buy
this house for,

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:31.720
the bigger their
commission will be.

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:33.620
Absolutely.

00:32:33.620 --> 00:32:34.330
OK?

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:39.155
So the person, the one
who hired agent, yes?

00:32:39.155 --> 00:32:41.280
AUDIENCE: So just a follow-up
to that question too,

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:44.460
so what's the
incentive for me then,

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:47.284
as a buyer, when I see
a property listing.

00:32:47.284 --> 00:32:49.200
Why don't I just go
directly to that property,

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:50.909
go to that real estate
agent and say, we

00:32:50.909 --> 00:32:52.200
have two ways we could do this.

00:32:52.200 --> 00:32:53.805
I can bring in my
real estate agent

00:32:53.805 --> 00:32:55.410
and you can half
your commission,

00:32:55.410 --> 00:32:57.898
or I can work with you,
and you can get double

00:32:57.898 --> 00:32:59.280
what you're going to get.

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:00.640
Why don't we play nice?

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:01.690
Like, do people do that?

00:33:01.690 --> 00:33:03.065
TRISHA OCONA
FRANCIS: We're going

00:33:03.065 --> 00:33:04.640
to go right into that right now.

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.350
The seller's agent.

00:33:06.350 --> 00:33:08.700
When you go into these
real estate websites,

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:12.950
and you see these houses for
sale, and you click that house,

00:33:12.950 --> 00:33:16.530
and you call up that real
estate agent, guess what?

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:19.440
That real estate agent is
working for the seller.

00:33:19.440 --> 00:33:23.060
So that term that the police
says, anything you say or do

00:33:23.060 --> 00:33:24.730
can and will be
held against you,

00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:26.950
is exactly what's happening.

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:30.310
Any single thing you
tell that agent who

00:33:30.310 --> 00:33:34.080
is working for that seller,
they will use against you.

00:33:34.080 --> 00:33:39.310
So you tell them you
just won the lotto.

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:41.140
What you think
they're going to do?

00:33:41.140 --> 00:33:45.030
They're going to tell the
seller, you won the lotto.

00:33:45.030 --> 00:33:50.760
You tell them that you
are approved for $500,000.

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:57.020
This house that you
want is $450,000.

00:33:57.020 --> 00:33:59.800
You put in the
offer for $420,000.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:01.760
They're going to
tell the seller,

00:34:01.760 --> 00:34:03.140
he's approved for $500,000.

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:05.720
He can come up.

00:34:05.720 --> 00:34:07.920
They're not working for you.

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:11.850
They're working
for their seller.

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:15.070
Now a buyer's agent.

00:34:15.070 --> 00:34:18.120
So just to go back,
what are they doing?

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:20.560
When you're working
for the seller,

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:23.420
you're helping that
seller market their house,

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:26.550
show their house, find
a qualified buyer,

00:34:26.550 --> 00:34:29.460
approve the buyers, right?

00:34:29.460 --> 00:34:31.389
That's what you're trying to do.

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:36.000
Where are you
working for a buyer,

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:37.830
we're helping you
shop for a house,

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:40.690
you may find houses you
like and send to the agent.

00:34:40.690 --> 00:34:43.020
The agent is going to
research that house.

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:46.030
The agent is going to find out
any secrets about that house.

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:48.199
What if the house
is in foreclosure?

00:34:48.199 --> 00:34:50.480
What if the asking
price of that house

00:34:50.480 --> 00:34:56.909
is $799,000, but that person
is in foreclosure for $500,000

00:34:56.909 --> 00:35:00.150
and needs to be
out in two months?

00:35:00.150 --> 00:35:02.830
Do you need to offer $799,000?

00:35:02.830 --> 00:35:03.890
No.

00:35:03.890 --> 00:35:06.040
That's what their real
estate agent's going to do.

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:08.710
I showed a house last year.

00:35:08.710 --> 00:35:12.562
The real estate agent who works
for the seller never showed up.

00:35:12.562 --> 00:35:15.780
I came with my client,
who were the buyers.

00:35:15.780 --> 00:35:20.350
When I opened the door, the
old woman, very sweet and nice,

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:22.210
her husband was
sitting on the sofa.

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:24.210
What do you think she
told me the whole way?

00:35:24.210 --> 00:35:26.140
My knees, my knees, my knees.

00:35:26.140 --> 00:35:28.100
I can't go up these
stairs any more.

00:35:28.100 --> 00:35:29.027
You like the house?

00:35:29.027 --> 00:35:30.110
You want to buy the house?

00:35:30.110 --> 00:35:31.700
How much you want to
buy the house for?

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:32.616
Can you buy the house?

00:35:32.616 --> 00:35:34.580
Please buy the house.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:38.190
I turned to my clients and said,
we can offer whatever you want.

00:35:38.190 --> 00:35:40.230
They gotta go.

00:35:40.230 --> 00:35:44.000
Because I was working
for my buyer, right?

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.880
Because they were telling
all the information.

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:49.300
And that's why, when you
have somebody working

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:52.060
for the seller, and you have
somebody working for the buyer,

00:35:52.060 --> 00:35:53.800
it's almost like two lawyers.

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:57.970
Listen, I tell my client,
don't say a thing.

00:35:57.970 --> 00:35:59.230
Let me talk.

00:35:59.230 --> 00:36:02.980
I was showing a house, a condo,
the other day, and the agent

00:36:02.980 --> 00:36:06.520
asked my client,
so what do you do?

00:36:06.520 --> 00:36:08.275
I said, talk to me.

00:36:10.940 --> 00:36:13.310
And then he says, yeah, so
the bathroom is up there,

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:14.850
he says, could you
please tell your client

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:16.100
that the bathroom is
up-- like, you know,

00:36:16.100 --> 00:36:17.724
he made a joke about
it the whole time.

00:36:17.724 --> 00:36:20.220
But listen, I'm very
serious about that.

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:21.180
Talk to me.

00:36:21.180 --> 00:36:23.370
Because anything you
say will be used--

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:25.370
and a lot of real estate
agents don't know that.

00:36:25.370 --> 00:36:28.350
Because, matter of fact, when
we're walking into the condo,

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:31.870
he collected his client--
the seller, I guess,

00:36:31.870 --> 00:36:34.450
doesn't live there anymore--
and he collected the mail.

00:36:34.450 --> 00:36:37.430
And he said, oh man, my
client got to go to court.

00:36:37.430 --> 00:36:41.151
And we're looking at him like,
your client got to go to court?

00:36:41.151 --> 00:36:41.650
Great.

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:43.316
You just gave me a
piece of information.

00:36:43.316 --> 00:36:45.709
Now I have to research
it and find out why

00:36:45.709 --> 00:36:47.000
your client has to go to court.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:48.530
And maybe now I don't
have to offer you

00:36:48.530 --> 00:36:50.940
what you are asking because
your client has to go to court.

00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:51.440
Yes?

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:53.190
AUDIENCE: I don't know if you're
going to get into this later,

00:36:53.190 --> 00:36:55.940
but like for properties that
are like going into foreclosure,

00:36:55.940 --> 00:36:57.601
like what is the
process for that?

00:36:57.601 --> 00:36:59.350
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS:
I have it at the end

00:36:59.350 --> 00:37:01.150
if we have extra time.

00:37:01.150 --> 00:37:02.750
But I kept it as a backup.

00:37:02.750 --> 00:37:03.470
Yes?

00:37:03.470 --> 00:37:06.800
AUDIENCE: Is it a good
idea to get pre-approvals

00:37:06.800 --> 00:37:09.464
at multiple price points, then?

00:37:09.464 --> 00:37:10.880
TRISHA OCONA
FRANCIS: Pre approval

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:12.120
at multiple price points.

00:37:12.120 --> 00:37:14.940
You should get a pre-approval
at what you could afford.

00:37:14.940 --> 00:37:16.700
Because I've seen
loan officers do that.

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:18.850
How much do you
want the loan for?

00:37:18.850 --> 00:37:20.200
How much you want the loan for?

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:21.590
How much can they afford?

00:37:21.590 --> 00:37:26.020
So do it at what-- now
if they approve you

00:37:26.020 --> 00:37:29.710
for $800,000, that doesn't
mean you could go to $800,000.

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:31.460
I'm going to get to
that in a few minutes.

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:33.280
Go at what you feel
you can afford.

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:35.440
You had a question.

00:37:35.440 --> 00:37:36.399
Yes?

00:37:36.399 --> 00:37:38.894
AUDIENCE: So there's a bit
of physical game there.

00:37:38.894 --> 00:37:41.727
Let's say I come in
with an all cash offer.

00:37:41.727 --> 00:37:44.226
That's something ideally I'd
want to disclose to the seller.

00:37:44.226 --> 00:37:46.681
Because they know they can trust
I'm not going to, you know,

00:37:46.681 --> 00:37:47.222
fail on that.

00:37:47.222 --> 00:37:51.490
But at the same time, it's kind
of telling them something too.

00:37:51.490 --> 00:37:54.300
How do you balance, you
know, showing yourself

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:58.256
as a worthy-- somebody who
can afford to actually go

00:37:58.256 --> 00:38:02.030
through with the purchase--
yet without saying, you know,

00:38:02.030 --> 00:38:07.790
about-- without disclosing that
there's little, how can I say?

00:38:07.790 --> 00:38:09.174
That you've got
a limited budget.

00:38:09.174 --> 00:38:11.340
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: One,
you need a representative

00:38:11.340 --> 00:38:12.720
to do that for you.

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:15.820
Because the other agents know
how to pick-- like I know,

00:38:15.820 --> 00:38:18.580
depending on what side, like
I can work on either side.

00:38:18.580 --> 00:38:20.320
I can work on the
seller's side, or I

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:21.025
can work on the buyer's side.

00:38:21.025 --> 00:38:22.733
And depending on the
side I'm working on,

00:38:22.733 --> 00:38:25.012
I know how to pick
and ask the questions.

00:38:25.012 --> 00:38:26.970
AUDIENCE: How would you
present that situation?

00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:30.120
Do you say, I've got a buyer,
and he's got an all cash offer.

00:38:30.120 --> 00:38:32.840
The seller is like, OK,
this is awesome, right?

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:35.502
But then that also tells
them that you might be--

00:38:35.502 --> 00:38:36.710
TRISHA OCONA FRANCIS: Loaded?

00:38:36.710 --> 00:38:39.044
AUDIENCE: --able to bid higher
than you otherwise would.

00:38:39.044 --> 00:38:40.418
TRISHA OCONA
FRANCIS: Not really,

00:38:40.418 --> 00:38:41.960
because-- this is what I do.

00:38:41.960 --> 00:38:46.200
If my client has a pre-approval,
or a bank statement--

00:38:46.200 --> 00:38:49.440
I had a client that had a
bank statement of $22 million

00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:50.680
on the statement.

00:38:50.680 --> 00:38:53.440
I'm not going to send
them over the $22 million.

00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:58.210
We got a statement
that shows less money.

00:38:58.210 --> 00:38:59.860
So they don't really
see how much money

00:38:59.860 --> 00:39:01.660
you're really working with.

00:39:01.660 --> 00:39:03.460
So this is my offer,
and then, also

00:39:03.460 --> 00:39:05.410
justify why you're
giving this offer.

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:08.030
So the house may
be asking $900,000,

00:39:08.030 --> 00:39:09.447
but you're only
offering $800,000.

00:39:09.447 --> 00:39:11.363
And you're saying, well,
I'm offering $800,000

00:39:11.363 --> 00:39:12.640
because I'm giving all cash.

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:14.026
All I need is a clear title.

00:39:14.026 --> 00:39:16.650
I can close in 30 days, so that
should be an incentive for you.

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:19.210
You don't have to wait for
someone who may not qualify.

00:39:19.210 --> 00:39:21.877
And two, listen, I need
to change the boiler.

00:39:21.877 --> 00:39:22.960
I need to change the roof.

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:25.190
These are the reasons
why I'm offering less.

00:39:25.190 --> 00:39:26.400
So you have to justify.

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:28.940
Now, once again, I said
you need a representative.

00:39:28.940 --> 00:39:32.211
Because the representative
knows how to talk to the person.

00:39:32.211 --> 00:39:32.710
Right?

00:39:32.710 --> 00:39:35.710
So this woman who came and
said her knees, her knees.

00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:37.670
If her representative
was there--

00:39:37.670 --> 00:39:40.970
if I was representing
her, I would have said,

00:39:40.970 --> 00:39:43.120
Mr. and Mrs. Jones,
please sit your butt down,

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:44.630
don't say a word.

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:46.010
Just sit still.

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:46.750
Right?

00:39:46.750 --> 00:39:48.460
But they didn't do that.

00:39:48.460 --> 00:39:52.750
So now I saw what was wrong,
and I was able to use that.

00:39:52.750 --> 00:39:55.680
Or, if I go show a house, and
the real estate agent's not

00:39:55.680 --> 00:40:00.169
there, right, they just
say whatever they want.

00:40:00.169 --> 00:40:01.960
Sometimes I'll go up
to another real estate

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:04.209
agent who I can tell doesn't
have that much knowledge,

00:40:04.209 --> 00:40:06.650
and say, how much
will the owners take?

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:09.710
So the house is asking
$500,000, and you just

00:40:09.710 --> 00:40:11.180
say, how much will
the owners take?

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:14.530
And they'll say, well, the
owners will take $450,000.

00:40:14.530 --> 00:40:16.427
And I'm like, who
do you work for?

00:40:16.427 --> 00:40:18.760
You're supposed to be getting
the owners the most money.

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:19.860
Why do they do that?

00:40:19.860 --> 00:40:21.910
Because they're looking
for a quick, fast deal.

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:25.360
The correct answer to say is,
the owner will take $500,000.

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:26.670
Put in an offer.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:27.170
Right?

00:40:27.170 --> 00:40:29.760
If I'm working for the seller.

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:30.260
OK.

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:34.090
So you have buyer's
agent, and then you

00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:36.010
have fiduciary responsibilities.

00:40:36.010 --> 00:40:38.620
So there's an agency
disclosure form

00:40:38.620 --> 00:40:40.280
that a real estate
agent is supposed

00:40:40.280 --> 00:40:43.520
to present to you as
soon as they meet you.

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:46.290
They're supposed to
present this form to you.

00:40:46.290 --> 00:40:47.400
It's not a contract.

00:40:47.400 --> 00:40:49.650
It'll say big and
bold, not a contract.

00:40:49.650 --> 00:40:51.350
It's if you're
renting an apartment,

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:53.390
or if you're buying
a house, selling,

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:54.610
and it's a disclosure form.

00:40:54.610 --> 00:40:56.730
State law says
that you must, they

00:40:56.730 --> 00:40:59.890
must sign it just to prove
that they presented it to you.

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:03.960
Because most people don't
know who works for them.

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:06.090
A lot of times they
think the person they

00:41:06.090 --> 00:41:07.750
call-- when they
look online-- is

00:41:07.750 --> 00:41:09.170
the person who works for them.

00:41:09.170 --> 00:41:12.150
You may see a real estate
agent, and one Sunday you

00:41:12.150 --> 00:41:14.670
see 10 houses with
that real estate agent.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:17.280
You talk about children,
you talk about family,

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:18.890
and then that real
estate agent shows

00:41:18.890 --> 00:41:20.856
you one of their listings
with their seller.

00:41:20.856 --> 00:41:22.230
You think the
agent works for you

00:41:22.230 --> 00:41:24.063
because you spent the
whole Sunday together,

00:41:24.063 --> 00:41:27.260
when, really, still, that
agent works for the seller.

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:30.040
So that disclosure form
completely tells you

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:31.000
who they work for.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:34.020
So now you know to
keep your mouth zip,

00:41:34.020 --> 00:41:36.670
or get your own
buyer representation.

00:41:36.670 --> 00:41:39.480
How do you remember the
fiduciary responsibilities?

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:40.190
Old car.

00:41:40.190 --> 00:41:41.090
It spells old car.

00:41:41.090 --> 00:41:43.650
This is how I teach it when
I teach it in the college.

00:41:43.650 --> 00:41:44.860
Obedience.

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:47.570
The person-- and this is for
the seller or the buyer's agent.

00:41:47.570 --> 00:41:49.670
The person that you
hired, a real estate agent

00:41:49.670 --> 00:41:52.280
that you hire, has to
be obedient to you.

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:53.150
Right?

00:41:53.150 --> 00:41:55.250
As long as not
discrimination, they

00:41:55.250 --> 00:41:59.160
have to be obedient and
follow, you know, whatever.

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:02.120
If you tell them to put
in an offer for $350,000,

00:42:02.120 --> 00:42:04.370
they can't put in an
offer for $355,000.

00:42:04.370 --> 00:42:07.060
They have to, you know,
go with what you say.

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:07.740
Loyalty.

00:42:07.740 --> 00:42:09.070
They are loyal to you.

00:42:09.070 --> 00:42:10.910
They can't be going
back and forth

00:42:10.910 --> 00:42:13.660
between the buyer
and the seller.

00:42:13.660 --> 00:42:14.990
Right?

00:42:14.990 --> 00:42:16.890
They owe you all that respect.

00:42:16.890 --> 00:42:18.410
Disclosure.

00:42:18.410 --> 00:42:21.500
Anything they know, they've
got to disclose to you.

00:42:21.500 --> 00:42:23.990
Now, when you buy
a house, if there's

00:42:23.990 --> 00:42:26.420
something wrong with
the house, by law

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:27.850
they must disclose that to you.

00:42:27.850 --> 00:42:30.660
They're not allowed to sell
you a lemon without telling you

00:42:30.660 --> 00:42:31.540
it's a lemon.

00:42:31.540 --> 00:42:33.960
That must be disclosed
automatically.

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:36.320
But, if I'm working for
a buyer, and I find out

00:42:36.320 --> 00:42:38.140
some good juice
about the seller,

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:40.040
I'm going to let the buyer know.

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:42.030
That's what they're
supposed to do.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:44.310
Confidentiality-- some
people don't want.

00:42:44.310 --> 00:42:46.270
I had a client a
while ago who did not

00:42:46.270 --> 00:42:49.006
want anyone-- a neighbor
was buying the house.

00:42:49.006 --> 00:42:50.630
She didn't want anyone
to know that she

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:52.100
was buying the house,
because she didn't

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:53.590
want the people on
the block to know

00:42:53.590 --> 00:42:54.630
that she was buying the house.

00:42:54.630 --> 00:42:56.296
She didn't even want
the tenants to know

00:42:56.296 --> 00:42:57.380
she was buying the house.

00:42:57.380 --> 00:43:00.450
So confidentiality is
very, very important.

00:43:00.450 --> 00:43:02.850
You also get a lot of people's
information sometimes.

00:43:02.850 --> 00:43:06.290
A loan officer gets your social
security number, your income,

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:08.750
but I mean, I get a
lot of information.

00:43:08.750 --> 00:43:09.250
Right?

00:43:09.250 --> 00:43:13.790
I helped a friend of mine
and his wife buy a house.

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:18.914
And his wife is pretty famous.

00:43:18.914 --> 00:43:20.830
And I know how much she
makes because I helped

00:43:20.830 --> 00:43:22.770
them buy their house, right?

00:43:22.770 --> 00:43:24.930
That's confidentiality.

00:43:24.930 --> 00:43:25.480
Right?

00:43:25.480 --> 00:43:27.230
So my father would
come to me and be like,

00:43:27.230 --> 00:43:28.890
so how much was their house?

00:43:28.890 --> 00:43:30.310
I'm like, none of your business.

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:31.768
Like you know, you
can't tell them,

00:43:31.768 --> 00:43:34.950
because that's
between you and them.

00:43:34.950 --> 00:43:36.820
Accountability.

00:43:36.820 --> 00:43:38.460
People are going
to give you things.

00:43:38.460 --> 00:43:40.845
They're going to give
you maybe some documents.

00:43:40.845 --> 00:43:42.220
You have to make
sure that you're

00:43:42.220 --> 00:43:44.860
accountable for everything,
and that you don't turn around

00:43:44.860 --> 00:43:46.284
later and say, oh, I lost that.

00:43:46.284 --> 00:43:47.950
Could you send that
to me again, please?

00:43:47.950 --> 00:43:49.450
You want to make
sure you have that.

00:43:49.450 --> 00:43:51.812
And reasonable care means
that the real estate

00:43:51.812 --> 00:43:53.520
agent knows what
they're doing, that they

00:43:53.520 --> 00:43:54.620
understand real estate.

00:43:54.620 --> 00:43:56.540
I always, when I
teach, I always tell

00:43:56.540 --> 00:44:01.400
my students, a lot of
people teach to pass a test.

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:03.810
I teach you to teach
you real estate.

00:44:03.810 --> 00:44:06.580
So it's very important that the
real estate agent you work with

00:44:06.580 --> 00:44:09.130
understands the
dynamics of real estate.

00:44:09.130 --> 00:44:11.630
So they can tell whether--
we're not roofers,

00:44:11.630 --> 00:44:14.510
we're not plumbers, but they
can tell that there's a leak.

00:44:14.510 --> 00:44:16.970
